Statistics ‘by’ Gender

Notes:

by(pf$friend_count, pf$gender, summary)
## pf$gender: female
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##       0      37      96     242     244    4923 
## -------------------------------------------------------- 
## pf$gender: male
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.

Who on average has more friends: men or women?

Response: Women

What’s the difference between the median friend count for women and men?

Response: ‘r 96-74’

Why would the median be a better measure than the mean?

Response: The data has a long-tail format, which means that the very few outliers with huge friend counts would skew the mean much higher than it should be. ***

User Ages

Notes:

qplot(x = age, data = pf, binwidth = 1, color = I("black"), fill = I("#8C70C9")) +

What do you notice?

Response: There is a large number of outliers at the high end of the spectrum that are skewing the data. The vast majority of users are concentrated around the 10-30 mark, which is intuitive given Facebook’s target audience. ***

The Spread of Memes

Notes: Using logarithms, data can be normalized to decrease the impact of over-dispersion. Log(0) is undefined, so add one to values that might be zero. Log10 basically transforms data into orders of magnitude instead of absolute values. ***

#no_scale <- qplot(x = friend_count+1, data = pf, binwidth = 50, color = I("black"), fill = I("#8C70C9"))

# This is better because the friendly labeling of the x axis is more readable. 
# log10 will label the axis with actual values instead of log units.
no_scale <- ggplot(aes(x = friend_count), data = pf) + geom_histogram()
log10_scale <- no_scale + scale_x_log10()
sqrt_scale <- no_scale + scale_x_sqrt()

grid.arrange(no_scale, log10_scale, sqrt_scale, ncol = 1)

qplot(x = gender,
        y = friend_count,
        data = subset(pf, !is.na(gender)),

    scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 1000)) +

Box Plots, Quartiles, and Friendships

Notes: coord_cartesian() is better for setting the y limits. scale_y_continuous() changes the actual values displayed.

by(pf$friendships_initiated, pf$gender, summary)
## pf$gender: female
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##     0.0    19.0    49.0   113.9   124.8  3654.0 
## -------------------------------------------------------- 
## pf$gender: male
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##     0.0    15.0    44.0   103.1   111.0  4144.0
qplot(x = gender,
        y = friendships_initiated,
        data = subset(pf, !is.na(gender)),
        geom = "boxplot") +
    coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 100)) +
    facet_wrap(~gender)
